05106nam a22007215i 9780812205480DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979741048  a97808122054807 a10.9783/97808122054802doi  a(DE-B1597)449397  a(OCoLC)794700617  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360202bisacsh1 aStanwood, Owen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Empire Reformed :bEnglish America in the Age of the Glorious Revolution /cOwen Stanwood. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b9 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly American Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction: Popery and Politics in the British Atlantic World -- tPart I. Empire Imagined -- tChapter 1. Imperial Designs -- tChapter 2. Catholics, Indians, and the Politics of Conspiracy -- tPart II. Empire Lost -- tChapter 3. Rumors and Rebellions -- tChapter 4. The Empire Turned Upside Down -- tPart III. Empire Regained -- tChapter 5. The Protestant Assault on French America -- tChapter 6. Ambivalent Bonds -- tEpilogue: Nicholson’s Redemption -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Empire Reformed tells the story of a forgotten revolution in English America—a revolution that created not a new nation but a new kind of transatlantic empire. During the seventeenth century, England's American colonies were remote, disorganized outposts with reputations for political turmoil. Colonial subjects rebelled against authority with stunning regularity, culminating in uprisings that toppled colonial governments in the wake of England's "Glorious Revolution" in 1688-89. Nonetheless, after this crisis authorities in both England and the colonies successfully rebuilt the empire, providing the cornerstone of the great global power that would conquer much of the continent over the following century.In The Empire Reformed historian Owen Stanwood illustrates this transition in a narrative that moves from Boston to London to Barbados and Bermuda. He demonstrates not only how the colonies fit into the empire but how imperial politics reflected—and influenced—changing power dynamics in England and Europe during the late 1600s. In particular, Stanwood reveals how the language of Catholic conspiracies informed most colonists' understanding of politics, serving first as the catalyst of rebellions against authority, but later as an ideological glue that held the disparate empire together. In the wake of the Glorious Revolution imperial leaders and colonial subjects began to define the British empire as a potent Protestant union that would save America from the designs of French "papists" and their "savage" Indian allies. By the eighteenth century, British Americans had become proud imperialists, committed to the project of expanding British power in the Americas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aAmerican Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package American Historyz978311041349608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220548040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812205480423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812205480.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Compl